We identified several videos with tag as “[None]”, which means these videos do not have a tag. We keep the tags with [None], and rename [None] as “NoTag”, as we suppose NoTag videos probably have lower trending days.

Get the cleaned data set for analysis

Ideas and Rules:

  1. Change tags = “[None]” to “NoTag” to reduce the naming issues.

  2. Add a column of the year video published.

  3. Calculate the number of trending days.

  4. Keep only one row for each video at the first trending day

# clean up the table
library(dplyr)

data_clean <- data_filtered %>%
  group_by(video_id) %>%
  mutate(tags = ifelse(tags == "[None]", "NoTag", tags)) %>%
  mutate(published_year = year(publishedAt)) %>%
  mutate(num_trending_days = n_distinct(trending_date)) %>%
  filter(trending_date == min(trending_date)) %>%
  rename(min_trending_date = trending_date, likes_first_day = likes, 
         dislikes_first_day = dislikes, comment_count_first_day = comment_count, view_count_first_day = view_count)

Title

For title, we use TF and TF-IDF term frequency to analyze the frequency of words in title of videos. We create data frame for TF values and TF-IDF values for each video.

# Create a corpus of the reviews from the "title" using library(tm).
# Examine the review in document “617”.
library(tm)
## NLP
corpus = Corpus(VectorSource(data_clean$title))
corpus[[617]][1]
## $content

# Preprocess the corpus of reviews created in the previous question using functions from library(tm).
# Specifically, Use tm_map to
# (a) transform text to lower case,
corpus = tm_map(corpus,FUN = content_transformer(tolower))
# (b) remove punctuation,
corpus = tm_map(corpus,FUN = removePunctuation)
# (c) remove English stopwords using the following dictionary tm::stopwords("english")
corpus = tm_map(corpus,FUN = removeWords,c(stopwords('english')))
# (d) remove numbers
corpus = tm_map(corpus,FUN = removeNumbers)
# (e) remove whitespace
corpus = tm_map(corpus,FUN = stripWhitespace)
# (f) stem words
corpus = tm_map(corpus,FUN = stemDocument)

Category_Name

For Category_Name, which is the category of the video, we do a variable transformation to tranform this variable to dummy variables. To avoid multicollinearity problem, we delete one of the dummy variable created: Travel & Events. When the dummy variables of all other variables is 0, the video is categorized as ‘Travel & Events’.

library(fastDummies)
# Create dummy variables for category_name
dummy_category = dummy_cols(data_clean$category_name)
# remove variables that would result in multicolinearity problems
dummy_category$`.data` = NULL
dummy_category$`.data_Travel & Events` = NULL

# Use sub() to replace ".data" with "category" in each column name
colnames(dummy_category) = sub("\\.data", "category", colnames(dummy_category))
colnames(dummy_category) = make.names(colnames(dummy_category))

The channelTitle has 7069 total values, we decide not to use channelTitle directly as one variable, because it takes too much time to operate these large amount of values. Therefore, we decided move on to use only part of the channelTitle as dummy variables We select channelTitles with frequency > 50 (total 47 channelTitles) and create dummy variables However, we noticed that there could also be multicollinearity problems because channels would probably be high correlated to tags, category, and title.

selected_channel <- channelTitle_df[channelTitle_df$Freq > 50, "Var1"]

Tags

For tags, we have two format of data. One is labeled as “NoTag”, and the other is labeled as a string of a number of tags a video have. For example: “brawadis|prank|basketball|skits|ghost|funny videos|vlog|vlogging|NBA|browadis|challenges|bmw i8|faze rug|faze rug brother|mama rug and papa rug”.

Our idea is to use both type of data in creating dummy variables which identifies a video has no tag, or is labeled as one of the tags in the tag string. For the data with tags, we splitted the tag string into blocks of words, and the dummy variable will show if that word exist in the tags string.

# create dummy variables of tags
# split the tags according to "|"
tag_list <- strsplit(data_clean$tags, "\\|")
# Convert the resulting list to a vector
tag_vec <- unlist(tag_list)
# Calculate the frequency of each label
tag_freq <- table(tag_vec)
tag_df <- data.frame(tag_freq) %>% arrange(desc(Freq))
# Get top 20 titles in Frequency

To improve our model predict accuracy, we decided not to use all of the tags as dummy variables. We selected part of them which could be better fitted and explained in our model.

Our idea is to use two groups of different numbers of tag dummy variables, and compare which group could have better prediction power. We select tags with frequency > 200, and tags with frequency > 120 as our dummy variables of interest in our model, as we suggest tags with larger frequency in our data could have higher prediction power.

We also noticed that when a video’s tag is “NoTag”, all other tag dummy variables should be 0, which could possibly result multicollinearity problems. However, our selection of only group of tag dummy variables reduced the problem. In our created dummy variables data frame, all other variables labeled as 0 does not necessarily means the Tag is “NoTag”, so we reduced the multicollinearity problem for tag dummy variable. Besides, as we are interested in investigating how a “NoTag” video could affect the number of trending days, we still keep the dummy variable “NoTag” in our analysis.

# select tags with frequency > 200
selected_tags <- tag_df[tag_df$Freq > 200, "tag_vec"]
library(stringr)

Solving multicollinearity problems

Method 1: remove highly correlated variables

To solve multicollinearity problems, our first idea is to remove highly correlated variables.

# remove variables with correlation > 0.7
# view_count_first_day - tag_video.games - tag_trolling - tag_touchdown - tag_top.plays - tag_sssniperwolf - tag_sports - 
# tag_sniper.wolf - tag_reaction - tag_react - tag_prank - tag_offense - tag_no.swearing - tag_NFL - tag_NBA - tag_meme - 
# tag_matpat - tag_Hip.Hop - tag_Hip - tag_highlights - tag_G.League - tag_funny.videos - tag_funny - tag_fox.sports - tag_espn -
# tag_defense - tag_best.plays - tag_Basketball - tag_American.Football - tag_100.days
model_removed_1 = num_trending_days~.-view_count_first_day - tag_video.games - tag_trolling - tag_touchdown - tag_top.plays - tag_sssniperwolf - tag_sports - 
  tag_sniper.wolf - tag_reaction - tag_react - tag_prank - tag_offense - tag_no.swearing - tag_NFL - tag_NBA - tag_meme - 
  tag_matpat - tag_Hip.Hop - tag_Hip - tag_highlights - tag_G.League - tag_funny.videos - tag_funny - tag_fox.sports - tag_espn -
  tag_defense - tag_best.plays - tag_Basketball - tag_American.Football - tag_100.days

lm_model2 = lm(model_removed_1,
               data=train_3)

#summary(lm_model2)

Method 3: use Ridge or Lasso regression

# Method 3: use Ridge or Lasso regression
library(glmnet)
## ：Matrix
## Loaded glmnet 4.1-7
X = model.matrix(num_trending_days~., data = train_3)
y = train_3$num_trending_days
#summary(model1.ridge)

# Perform cross-validation to select lambda
cv.ridge <- cv.glmnet(X, y, alpha=0) # rigde regression
cv.lasso <- cv.glmnet(X, y, alpha=1) # lasso regression

# Plot cross-validation results
plot(cv.ridge)

plot(cv.lasso)

# Extract optimal lambda values
lambda.ridge <- cv.ridge$lambda.min
lambda.lasso <- cv.lasso$lambda.min

# Fit final models using optimal lambda values
fit.ridge <- glmnet(X, y, alpha=0, lambda=lambda.ridge)
fit.lasso <- glmnet(X, y, alpha=1, lambda=lambda.lasso)

# Predict
test_y = test_3$num_trending_days
test_X = model.matrix(num_trending_days~., data = test_3)

# Make predictions on test set
pred.ridge <- predict(fit.ridge, newx = test_X)
pred.lasso <- predict(fit.lasso, newx = test_X)

# Calculate RMSE for each model
rmse.ridge <- sqrt(mean((pred.ridge - test_y)^2))
rmse.lasso <- sqrt(mean((pred.lasso - test_y)^2))

# Print RMSE values
cat("RMSE (ridge) = ", rmse.ridge, "\n") # 1.734175 
## RMSE (ridge) =  1.734175
cat("RMSE (lasso) = ", rmse.lasso, "\n") # 1.731986 
## RMSE (lasso) =  1.731986
# lasso works better 
# lasso improved tmse best so far

Lasso regression has the best prediction performance so far.

Bar plot:

First define a function with input of coef_table (coefficient table), coef_name (the type of coefficient start with certain name), top, bot to be the top and bottom number of variables we want to show.

library(stringr)
library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)
library(forcats)

plot_coefficients <- function(coef_table, coef_name, top = 5, bot = 5) {
  # Create table of coefficients starting with specified coefficient name
  coef <- coef_table %>%
    filter(coeff != 0) %>%
    filter(str_detect(variable, str_c("^", coef_name))) %>%
    arrange(desc(coeff))
  
  # Select top and bottom coefficients based on input arguments
  coef_top <- head(coef, top)
  coef_bot <- tail(coef, bot)
  
  # Combine top and bottom coefficients and create bar plot
  coef_plot <- rbind(coef_top, coef_bot)
  coef_plot$variable <- fct_reorder(coef_plot$variable, coef_plot$coeff, .desc = FALSE) # Reorder
  bar_plot <- ggplot(coef_plot, aes(x = variable, y = coeff, fill = coeff < 0)) +
    geom_col() +
    scale_fill_manual(values = c("blue", "orange"), labels = c("Positive", "Negative")) +
    coord_flip() +
    labs(x = "Variable", y = "Coefficient", fill = "Sign") +
    ggtitle(str_c("Top and Bottom Coefficients for ", coef_name, " Variables")) +
    theme_bw()
  
  # Display bar plot
  print(bar_plot)
  
  # Return and output the coefficient table
  return(coef_plot)
}

library(glmnet)
X_2022 <- model.matrix(num_trending_days ~ . - published_year, data = train_2022)
y_2022 <- train_2022$num_trending_days

cv.lasso_2022 <- cv.glmnet(X_2022, y_2022, alpha = 1)

fit.lasso_2022 <- glmnet(X_2022, y_2022, alpha = 1, lambda = cv.lasso_2022$lambda.min)

test_y_2022 <- test_2022$num_trending_days
test_X_2022 <- model.matrix(num_trending_days ~ . - published_year, data = test_2022)

pred.lasso_2022 <- predict(fit.lasso_2022, newx = test_X_2022)

rmse.lasso_2022 <- sqrt(mean((pred.lasso_2022 - test_y_2022)^2)); rmse.lasso_2022

  rownames_to_column(var = "variable") %>%
  select(variable, s0) %>%
